title: For Sale:  70%. Markings
postcontent: All-original Colt Special Contract Model 1863 Rifle/Musket...this desirable, Colt-made longarm was manufactured at the Hartford factory in 1863. Far less common on the market than the Springfield Rifle/Musket, the Colt encorporated features from both the Springfield and British Enfield, as well as design innovations from Samuel Colt and the Colt firm. The rifle is marked correctly, with VP and New Jersey markings on the barrel, corresponding dates on the barrel and lock plate, 'US' mark on the buttplate tang, and a crisp 'NJ' inspection cartouche on the stock's left flat opposite the lockplate. Retaining the original sling swivels, correct ramrod, and 'US'-marked bayonet in very fine to excellent condition, the rifle has seen no refinish or restoration, and is in superb working order. An outstanding example of a highly sought-after Civil War collectible, this issued, mid-war Colt would be a fine investment and an excellent addition to the advanced collection.Condition:Very fine approaching excellent, the metal surfaces are univerally and correctly in the white, and have no rust or deep pitting. There is carbon spotting, oxidation staining, and old lubricant, as well as powder flash corrossion around the breech, but the metal surfaces overall rate at 70%. Markings are well-struck on both metal and wood, correct, and the dates, 1863, are matching on the lockplate and barrel. Furniture is in correspondingly very fine condition, with knackering, service handling marks, pressure dents and scarpes, but no repairs, cracks or chips. Additionally, feathering of the wood and the crispness of the 'NJ' cartouche confirm no sanding or refinish. Mechanical function appears very strong, with the nipple being clean and the hammer holding full and half-cock firmly, as well as crisp trigger pull. The bore has not been examined.

title: For Sale:  1985 WINCHESTER 1200
postcontent: The Winchester Model 1200 was introduced in 1964 as a low-cost replacement for the venerable Model 12. A small number of these weapons were acquired by the United States Army in 1968 and 1969. The military style Model 1200 was essentially the same weapon as the civilian version, except it had a ventilated handguard, sling swivels, and a bayonet lug. The Model 1200 was succeeded by the Winchester Model 1300 in 1983 when U.S. Repeating Arms Company became the manufacturer of Winchester firearms. The Model 1200 was the first shotgun to utilize a rotary bolt with four locking lugs secured within the barrel extension.shipping and insurance cost $35
